MESSAGE TYPE :::: INITIAL
UID :::: 1179981
SUBJECT :::: CUIABA--HOW TO KEEP COMMUNICATIONS PRIVILEGED
KEY(s) :::: ['his', 'him']
SENDER :::: 78022
RECEIVERS :::: [1635, 90544, 3098, 56127, 53072, 96364, 1926, 781, 79125, 42477, 40190, 88334, 55900, 34740, 36551, 30085, 19235, 40537, 19235]
COUNT :::: 412

ORIGINAL MESSAGE: 


The last thing you want is to be cross examined on your originally innocent
email, now a "smoking gun" expanded into a 6 foot exhibit in court or
arbitration. There are a number of precautions we can all take to prevent
written material,  including emails from becoming evidence in litigation or
arbitration.  Here are some guidelines:

1. Because we are preparing for litigation or arbitration, all
communications, correspondence, emails, documents, agendas, presentations
etc. relating in any way to the force majeure claims, the change orders,
defaults, termination, the consent (absence of) etc. should have the
following notation: "prepared at the direction of counsel in anticipation of
litigation--attorney/client privilege."  This includes presentation
materials/reports to Rebecca McDonald or upper management, etc.

2.  If business people or any other non-lawyers are going to ask for
information of the participants in the project, you should couch your
requests in language that suggests you are acting as agents for counsel.  In
other words, your requests for information should state,  "We have been asked
by counsel to assist in gathering information in preparation for litigation.
To assist us in assisting counsel we would appreciate it if you would provide
the following information." Or ask me and I'll send an email or give
instruction.

3.  There is no guaranty that even with these measures the communications
will remain privileged.  As a result, the less in writing from one business
person to another the better.  All written communications that contain
assessments of the facts, such as opinions as to what happened, etc should be
addressed directly to John Gardiner (jgardine@skadden.com) or me and only to
Gardiner or me.  Opinions are smoking guns.  Think before you write things
down or before you fire off an email.  Use the phone when you can.

4.  For those of you participating in the investigation of force majeure
claims: Jim Bermudez of Wilson Management Associates is conducting an
investigation of the force majeure claims and change orders.  Because Jim has
been hired by counsel to conduct the investigation in anticipation of
litigation, his notes, thought processes, conversations etc. are privileged.
The best approach for each of you to take is simply to talk with Jim and
allow him to take notes. You should avoid putting anything in writing, let
him do it.  If you must write something, remember to note that it is
"prepared at the direction of counsel in anticipation of litigation" and
address it to John Gardiner or me, even if you give it to Jim.  When in
doubt, just call or email me and I'll help you figure out what to do.

5.  Along those same lines, if anyone on the team decides an internal
investigation or study should be conducted for any reason, and you decide you
need to hire a consultant or expert to do it, please let me know so we can
retain them through counsel.  All it takes is a letter to protect the
investigation.  This is especially true with technical experts and
investigations about any technical problems with the plant.  Because it is
foreseeable that we could end up in litigation with the contractor or with an
insurance company over coverage resulting from technical problems, it is
prudent to protect these types of materials if you can.  Remember, this
happened to us in the Dominican Republic and it is happening right now in
India.

6.   On the weekly calls or meetings where attorneys are present, get in the
habit of stating so in your notes and write Attorney Client Privilege at the
beginning.  This is a good, routine business practice regardless of what you
are working on.

Please call or email me if you have any questions. 713-345-6159.
Regards,
Michelle



