email, now a "smoking gun" expanded into a 6 foot exhibit in court or
arbitration. There are a number of precautions we can all take to prevent
written material,  including emails from becoming evidence in litigation or
arbitration.  Here are some guidelines:

1. Because we are preparing for litigation or arbitration, all
communications, correspondence, emails, documents, agendas, presentations
etc. relating in any way to the force majeure claims, the change orders,
defaults, termination, the consent (absence of) etc. should have the
following notation: "prepared at the direction of counsel in anticipation of
litigation--attorney/client privilege."  This includes presentation
materials/reports to Rebecca McDonald or upper management, etc.

2.  If business people or any other non-lawyers are going to ask for
information of the participants in the project, you should couch your
requests in language that suggests you are acting as agents for counsel.  In
other words, your requests for information should state,  "We have been asked
by counsel to assist in gathering information in preparation for litigation.
To assist us in assisting counsel we would appreciate it if you would provide
the following information." Or ask me and I'll send an email or give
instruction.

3.  There is no guaranty that even with these measures the communications
will remain privileged.  As a result, the less in writing from one business
person to another the better.  All written communications that contain
assessments of the facts, such as opinions as to what happened, etc should be
addressed directly to John Gardiner (jgardine@skadden.com) or me and only to
Gardiner or me.  Opinions are smoking guns.  Think before you write things
down or before you fire off an email.  Use the phone when you can.

